# OpenManus Project Analysis

## 1. Project Introduction

OpenManus is an open-source framework designed for building general AI agents that can execute various tasks using multiple tools. The project aims to provide a versatile agent system that can solve diverse problems without requiring an invite code, making AI agent technology more accessible. The core goals include supporting both local and MCP (Model Context Protocol) tools, enabling browser automation, code execution, file operations, and web search capabilities.

The framework is built by contributors from MetaGPT and is designed for developers and researchers interested in AI agent development. It provides a modular architecture that allows for easy extension and integration of new tools and capabilities. The project supports multiple language interfaces (English, Chinese, Korean, Japanese) and includes experimental features like A2A protocol integration.

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown

The OpenManus architecture consists of several core components organized in a modular structure:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Client Interface] --> B[Main Agent]
    B --> C[Tool Management]
    C --> D[Local Tools]
    C --> E[MCP Tools]
    B --> F[LLM Integration]
    F --> G[Multiple LLM Providers]
    B --> H[Sandbox Environment]
    D --> I[Python Execution]
    D --> J[Browser Automation]
    D --> K[File Operations]
    D --> L[Web Search]
    H --> M[Docker Container]
```

### Design Patterns

The project implements several key design patterns:

- **Factory Pattern**: Used in the `Manus.create()` method for agent initialization
- **Strategy Pattern**: Implemented in search engine selection with primary and fallback engines
- **Observer Pattern**: Utilized in the agent's state management system
- **Dependency Injection**: Applied through Pydantic's Field and model_validator
- **Singleton Pattern**: Employed in the Config class for global configuration access

### System Relationships

The components interact through a well-defined hierarchy where the main agent orchestrates tool usage based on LLM decisions:

```mermaid
graph TD
    Manus[Manus Agent] -->|Uses| ToolCollection[ToolCollection]
    Manus -->|Communicates with| LLM[LLM]
    Manus -->|Manages| Sandbox[Sandbox]
    ToolCollection -->|Contains| PythonExecute[PythonExecute]
    ToolCollection -->|Contains| BrowserUse[BrowserUseTool]
    ToolCollection -->|Contains| WebSearch[WebSearch]
    ToolCollection -->|Contains| FileOps[StrReplaceEditor]
    LLM -->|Connects to| OpenAI[OpenAI API]
    LLM -->|Connects to| Anthropic[Anthropic API]
    LLM -->|Connects to| Ollama[Ollama]
    Sandbox -->|Runs in| Docker[Docker Container]
```

### Data Flow

The data flow follows a request-response pattern with state management:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    User[User Input] --> Manus[Manus Agent]
    Manus --> Memory[Memory Storage]
    Manus --> LLM[LLM Request]
    LLM -->|Response| Manus
    Manus -->|Tool Selection| Tool[Selected Tool]
    Tool -->|Execution| Sandbox[Sandbox Environment]
    Sandbox -->|Result| Manus
    Manus -->|Update Memory| Memory
    Manus -->|Final Response| User
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- [main.py](main.py)
- [run_mcp.py](run_mcp.py)

- [sandbox_main.py](sandbox_main.py)

### Core Modules
- [app/agent/manus.py](app/agent/manus.py)
- [app/llm.py](app/llm.py)
- [app/config.py](app/config.py)
- [app/sandbox/core/sandbox.py](app/sandbox/core/sandbox.py)
- [app/tool/base.py](app/tool/base.py)

### Configuration Approach
- [config/config.example.toml](config/config.example.toml)
- [config/mcp.example.json](config/mcp.example.json)

### External Dependencies
- [requirements.txt](requirements.txt)

### Integration Points
- [protocol/a2a/app/main.py](protocol/a2a/app/main.py)
- [app/tool/chart_visualization](app/tool/chart_visualization)
- [app/daytona](app/daytona)

### Component Relationships

```mermaid
graph LR
    Manus[Manus Agent] -->|Uses| Tools[ToolCollection]
    Manus -->|Configured by| Config[Config]
    Manus -->|Communicates via| LLM[LLM]
    Tools -->|Includes| Python[PythonExecute]
    Tools -->|Includes| Browser[BrowserUseTool]
    Tools -->|Includes| WebSearch[WebSearch]
    Tools -->|Includes| FileOps[StrReplaceEditor]
    Tools -->|Includes| AskHuman[AskHuman]
    LLM -->|Supports| OpenAI[OpenAI]
    LLM -->|Supports| Anthropic[Anthropic]
    LLM -->|Supports| Azure[Azure OpenAI]
    LLM -->|Supports| Ollama[Ollama]
    Manus -->|Executes in| Sandbox[DockerSandbox]
    Config -->|Loaded from| TOML[config.toml]
    Config -->|MCP Servers| MCP[mcp.json]
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview

OpenManus provides a comprehensive AI agent framework with the following key features:

- **Multi-tool Support**: Integration of various tools for different tasks
- **MCP Protocol**: Support for Model Context Protocol for remote tool access
- **Sandboxed Execution**: Secure code execution in isolated Docker containers
- **Web Browsing**: Browser automation capabilities for web interaction
- **Code Execution**: Safe Python code execution with timeout and safety restrictions
- **Web Search**: Multi-engine search with fallback capabilities
- **File Operations**: File creation, editing, and management
- **Multi-LLM Support**: Compatibility with various LLM providers

### Implementation Highlights
- [app/agent/manus.py](app/agent/manus.py#L17-L164): Manus agent implementation with MCP server integration
- [app/llm.py](app/llm.py): LLM integration with token counting and retry logic
- [app/sandbox/core/sandbox.py](app/sandbox/core/sandbox.py): Docker-based sandbox implementation
- [app/tool/python_execute.py](app/tool/python_execute.py): Secure Python execution with multiprocessing
- [app/tool/web_search.py](app/tool/web_search.py): Multi-engine web search with content fetching

### Feature Architecture

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> Processing: User Request
    Processing --> ToolSelection: LLM Response
    ToolSelection --> PythonExecution: python_execute
    ToolSelection --> BrowserAction: browser_use
    ToolSelection --> WebSearch: web_search
    ToolSelection --> FileOperation: str_replace
    ToolSelection --> HumanInput: ask_human
    PythonExecution --> Sandbox: Execute Code
    BrowserAction --> Browser: Control Browser
    WebSearch --> SearchEngine: Query Web
    FileOperation --> FileSystem: Modify File
    HumanInput --> User: Request Input
    User --> Processing: Provide Response
    Sandbox --> Processing: Return Output
    Browser --> Processing: Return State
    SearchEngine --> Processing: Return Results
    FileSystem --> Processing: Confirm Operation
    Processing --> FinalResponse: Complete Task
    FinalResponse --> Idle: terminate
```
</blog>
